




TY  - JOUR
T1  - Interpreting Economic Time Series
AU  - Sargent, Thomas J.
Y1  - 1981/04/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260963
DO  - 10.1086/260963
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 213
EP  - 248
VL  - 89
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper explores some of the implications for econometric practice of the principle that people's observed behavior will change when their constraints change. In dynamic contexts, a proper definition of people's constraints includes among them laws of motion that describe the evolution of the taxes they must pay and the prices of the goods that they buy and sell. Changes in agents' perceptions of these laws of motion (or constraints) will in general produce changes in the schedules that describe the choices they make as a function of the information that they possess. Until very recently, received dynamic econometric practice ignored this principle. The practice of dynamic econometrics should be changed so that it is consistent with the principle that people's rules of choice are influenced by their constraints. This is a substantial undertaking and involves major adjustments in the ways that we formulate, estimate, and simulate econometric models.
AB  - This paper explores some of the implications for econometric practice of the principle that people's observed behavior will change when their constraints change. In dynamic contexts, a proper definition of people's constraints includes among them laws of motion that describe the evolution of the taxes they must pay and the prices of the goods that they buy and sell. Changes in agents' perceptions of these laws of motion (or constraints) will in general produce changes in the schedules that describe the choices they make as a function of the information that they possess. Until very recently, received dynamic econometric practice ignored this principle. The practice of dynamic econometrics should be changed so that it is consistent with the principle that people's rules of choice are influenced by their constraints. This is a substantial undertaking and involves major adjustments in the ways that we formulate, estimate, and simulate econometric models.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260963
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260963
Y2  - 2024/03/23
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Activist Monetary Policy under Rational Expectations
AU  - Howitt, Peter
Y1  - 1981/04/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260964
DO  - 10.1086/260964
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 249
EP  - 269
VL  - 89
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The purpose of this paper is to argue that the pursuit of an activist monetary policy may make economic sense even when people's expectations are formed rationally. The paper presents a simple model in which (1) prices are costly to adjust, (2) there is uncertainty concerning the parameters affecting aggregate demand, and (3) there are positive costs of gathering and processing information. By reference to this model it can be shown that an activist monetary policy may or may not be useful in offsetting aggregate disturbances, depending upon the extent of information costs and of parameter uncertainty.
AB  - The purpose of this paper is to argue that the pursuit of an activist monetary policy may make economic sense even when people's expectations are formed rationally. The paper presents a simple model in which (1) prices are costly to adjust, (2) there is uncertainty concerning the parameters affecting aggregate demand, and (3) there are positive costs of gathering and processing information. By reference to this model it can be shown that an activist monetary policy may or may not be useful in offsetting aggregate disturbances, depending upon the extent of information costs and of parameter uncertainty.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260964
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260964
Y2  - 2024/03/23
