TY  - JOUR
T1  - Transaction Costs, Order Placement Strategy, and Existence of the Bid-Ask Spread
AU  - Cohen, Kalman J.
AU  - Maier, Steven F.
AU  - Schwartz, Robert A.
AU  - Whitcomb, David K.
Y1  - 1981/04/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260966
DO  - 10.1086/260966
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 287
EP  - 305
VL  - 89
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - By considering investor order placement strategy, this paper demonstrates that transaction costs cause bid-ask spreads to be an equilibrium property of asset markets. With transaction costs, the probability of a limit order executing does not go to unity as the order is placed infinitesimally close to a counterpart market quote; thus, with certainty of execution at the counterpart market quote, a "gravitational pull" is generated that keeps counterpart quotes from being placed infinitesimally close to each other. An equilibrium spread is defined and its size linked to market thinness; implications are noted for the design of a trading system.
AB  - By considering investor order placement strategy, this paper demonstrates that transaction costs cause bid-ask spreads to be an equilibrium property of asset markets. With transaction costs, the probability of a limit order executing does not go to unity as the order is placed infinitesimally close to a counterpart market quote; thus, with certainty of execution at the counterpart market quote, a "gravitational pull" is generated that keeps counterpart quotes from being placed infinitesimally close to each other. An equilibrium spread is defined and its size linked to market thinness; implications are noted for the design of a trading system.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260966
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260966
Y2  - 2024/03/23
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Land Value Capitalization in Local Public Finance
AU  - Starrett, David A.
Y1  - 1981/04/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260967
DO  - 10.1086/260967
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 306
EP  - 327
VL  - 89
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We explore the conditions under which the welfare benefits of local public goods projects will be capitalized into land values. We find two types of sufficient conditions, one involving similar communities and the other involving differentiated communities. The form of capitalization differs between these cases, and we explore the nature of these differences. We also examine intermediate cases and identify models in which there will be no capitalization.
AB  - We explore the conditions under which the welfare benefits of local public goods projects will be capitalized into land values. We find two types of sufficient conditions, one involving similar communities and the other involving differentiated communities. The form of capitalization differs between these cases, and we explore the nature of these differences. We also examine intermediate cases and identify models in which there will be no capitalization.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260967
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260967
Y2  - 2024/03/23
